), the southwestern PK 32 forest (Raxworthy et al ., umpublished,), Parc National de Zombitse (Raxworthy et al . 1994 ), and Vohibasia (
Goodman et al . 1997
), and the northwestern RS d'Ankarafantsika (
Ramanamanjato & Rabibisoa, 2002
;
Raselimanana, 2008
) did not provide any evidence for the occurrence of
A. meva
n. sp.
although numerous other burrowing species (skinks and frogs) were collected in these surveys. The species appears to show a preference for large rotten logs retaining a certain degree of humidity but in general in parts of the rainforest with relatively dry soils. Based on our finding in Marotandrano and Makira, this new species is not rare but probably has a quite strict ecological specificity with respect to its microhabitat (
Fig. 8
).
